Comment: Measurements refer to area  of 14 km2 located on Etna's western flank at an altitude between 1100 and 1900 m a.s.l., along the active W-Rift. TheW-Rift is one of the three main volcanic rift zones that affect the Mount Etna edifice.
Soil diffuse degassing within an area of about 2.5 km2 located on the lower south-western flank of Mt Etna volcano.
Soil diffuse degassing from Beach Village area. CO2 fluxes measurements have been collected in randomly distributed points on the Playa village by covering an area of 227,300 m2.
Soil diffuse degassing at Ginostra crater area, Stromboli.  CO2 fluxes have been measured randomly by covering an area of about 17,389 m2.

Soil diffuse degassing. CO2 fluxes have been detected in randomly distributed points on the
Ginostra Village area by covering an area of 171,219 m2.
CO2 flux measurements from soil diffuse degassing have been measured in 19 points  randomly distributed on the Punta Lena area by covering a surface of 2381 m2.
CO2 flux measurements of soil diffuse degassing have been collected in randomly distributed points on the Scari area by covering an area of 136,400 m2.
Soil diffuse degassing along the slope of the Stromboli's crateric area. CO2 fluxes have been measured in randomly distributed points on the Slope crater surface by covering an area of 659,900 m2.
Soil diffuse degassing in the Village area of Vulcano island.
Diffuse soil degassing in the Istmo area
CO2 fluxes from soil diffuse degassing have been measured in randomly distributed points on the Crater surface by covering  an area of 67,500 m2.
Diffuse gaseous emissions on the summit area of La Fossa crater, Vulcano island.

Site_Name: Ghiacciaio (Vedretta) Orientale di Sassolungo (Oestl. Lenkestein oder Lankstein Ferner) II

Comment: The site in object is placed at the slopes of the "Pizzo Scavarrante, in locality  "Feudo di Censo". The site, situated in a farmer, can be reached starting from the near country of Bivona (AG), distant about 4 km in SSE direction.

Take the State Road 447 from Catania to Gela and take the fourth exit to Palagonia. There is also a sign indicating Mofeta dei Palici. Follow this indication and after slightly more than 2 km there is the entrance of the plant where CO2 is extracted from the former lake. The site is into this private property. The old lake is now covered with a concrete dome that was used in the past to collect the gas and direct it through pipes to the plant. Today the gas is pumped directly from wells around the lake and gas bubbles in water only when the plant is not operating.
Close to Caprese Michelangelo, a couple of km from Dicciano, several bubbling pools are easily accessible.

NE of Amiata Mt. The CO2 discharge is well indicated and with fancy.

NE of Amiata Mt. Typical depression from the bottom of which a CO2-rich phase is discharged.

Gas emission iside an ancient Roman pool

The CO2 vent is located in a pubblic park near Oriolo Romano. The water pool in used for thermal bath
Vigorous vent emission inside a depression
Bubbling pool of about 1.5 m in diameter where a CO2-rich gas vigorously is released.

Several dry vents in the surrounding area of the village. Easy access no indication of the emission
Inside one of the most impressive CO2 manifestations in Tuscany called Inferno, NE of Amiata Mt. It a 1 inch wide hole  discharging CO2 that can be felt at 1 m of distance with a hand.
Several dry vents are present in the area without any warning singals.
NE of Amiata Mt, at the entrance of the old Hg mine two plastic tubes discharge CO2 in a well protected area
NE of Amiata Mt. Close the source of the Lavinate creek. A hole on the left creek bank releases CO2. Easy access through CAI pathways
Large area of diffuse emission with several vents where CO2 is more consistently released. The area is also named Pereta

The area covers about 100 square meters, characterized by a slit on the ground with a length of about 20 meters and depth of a few tens of centimeters, from which it has the greatest gas release. From this slot if they branch off at right angles to numerous others.

Strong gas emission inside a water pool. The gas emission is located in the forest.

This site is located along a city street into the village of Belpasso on the south flank of Etna. It is visible just because of a large metal pipe that is located on a side of the street and was intended to vent the steam from the fumarole into the atmosphere.

This site is located south of the village of Santa Venerina on the eastern flank of Etna, close to an industry of dairies. It is accessible from the road that connects Santa Venerina to Fleri, taking a small road to the industry named Zappalà . The largest emission is inside the industry, but some fumarole emissions are inside a private land where ships are grouped inside a fence.

From the village of Valverde take the road that leads to the monastry called Eremo di S.Anna. After a few hundred meters, after the public library, there is a gate (the first gate on the right) that leads to the property where the emissions occur.
BC fumarole is a new degassing vent opened in 2008, within the Solfatara crater, Pozzuoli.

several deposits of pyrite-barite, Cu sulfides in sediments from summit calderas of submerged volcano; Eckhardt et al. (1997): "A TV profile on Palinuro showed the occurrence of yellow (Fe oxyhydroxide or nontronite), black (Mn oxide), and white (sulfate) halos in the sediment and opaqueness in the overlying water."; Petersen et al. (2008): "TV-guided grab sampling at Palinuro retrieved warm (Tmax = 60 C) native sulphur cemented sediments indicating that hydrothermal activity is ongoing in the study area."; Walker et al. (2011): "An ORP anomaly of -160 mv was located at the west end of Palinuro where vent fluids up to 54 C were found. Living tubeworms, bacterial mats of various colors and textures, and small chimneys and globular spires coated with iron oxide having bright-green interiors indicative of the iron-rich hydrothermal clay nontronite were found at actively venting areas on Palinuro."; Carey et al. (2012): "tubeworms (siboglinidae) in the vicinity of ... (54 C) venting on the western end of Palinuro Seamount", "On Palinuro’s eastern end, there was also evidence of low-temperature hydrothermal venting from spires up to 30 cm in height. ... The discovery of active venting at each summit along most of Palinuro’s 50 km length..."
Source data: Menini et al., 2023; Rizzo et al., 2022

Comment: Heinicke et al. (2009): "continuous monitoring carried out between 2006 and 2007, coupled with the VLP seismicity recorded at the nearby Stromboli Island, and the helium isotopes recorded at both the islands, provide the indication that the modifications at the submarine venting fluids off Panarea are related to the seismic activity of Stromboli, thereby indicating that a common degassing source, probably made of magma intrusions along the N40°E fault, affects both volcanoes"; Carey et al. (2012): "small seamount south of Stromboli. … Previous dredging of Casoni Seamount recovered volcanic samples that were warm. No hydrothermal venting was discovered at Casoni..."
Source data: Menini et al., 2023; Rizzo et al., 2022

Comment: Lupton et al. (2011): "Of the seven bottles sampled, only a single bottle had a clear excess in 3He, and this was a fairly weak signal about 3% above the V07B-12 background in ?3He units (Figure 11). However, the along-axis tow over Sisifo (T07B-13) did detect a weak particle anomaly over the southeastern section of the seamount, where no discrete samples were collected (Figure 11a). Thus it is possible that some hydrothermal activity may have gone undetected in this portion of the seamount."
Source data: Menini et al., 2023; Rizzo et al., 2022

Comment: offshore area north of Salina; Gamberi et al. (1997): "In the western high, large areas of the seafloor are extensively covered by mounds of Fe-rich, semiconsolidated crusts ... The presence of these deposits on the seafloor implies that the Secca de1 Capo region has been affected by hydrothermalism in the recent past."; Lupton et al. (2011): "found a small 3He excess at about 200 m depth"
Source data: Menini et al., 2023; Rizzo et al., 2022

Comment: Eckhardt et al. (1997): "Our data support the idea that the Mn deposits formed as a result of submarine hydrothermal activity associated with subduction-related processes"; Walker et al. (2011): "At Enarete volcano, we found venting fluids with temperatures up to 5 C above ambient as well as small, fragile iron-oxide chimneys. The most intense ORP anomaly (-140 mv) occurred at a depth of about 495 m on the southeast side of the volcano, with smaller anomalies (-10 to -20 mv) more common as the ROV moved upslope to the summit."; Carey et al. (2012): "In some areas at the summit, fluids with temperatures up to 5 C above the ambient seawater were actively discharging. Bacteria were common in these areas, and small (a few tens of centimeters in height), fragile chimneys composed of iron oxides dotted the seafloor"
Source data: Menini et al., 2023; Rizzo et al., 2022

Comment: Walker et al. (2011): "ORP anomalies (-1 to -22 mv) were measured at several locations, primarily along the walls of the crescent-shaped collapse area (or possible caldera) east of the Eolo summit."; Carey et al. (2012): "we found evidence of hydrothermal venting at a number of sites"
Source data: Menini et al., 2023; Rizzo et al., 2022

Comment: Uchupi & Ballard (1989): "we did not encounter any evidence of active hydrothermal activity (smokers) during our survey [Argo video system]. Shimmering water indicative of active hydrothermal activity was noted during a cruise to the area in 1989 aboard R.V. Star Hercules.... The two north-south passes that we made across the shallow peak at the northeast end of Marsili Seamount suggest that most of the peak may be mantled by hydrothermal deposits."; email from Sven Petersen that included image from ROV Cherokee in 2006: "We have certainly seen low-temperature diffuse outflow at Marsili based on the occurrence of Fe-oxyhydroxide chimneys capped by bacterial mats."; no value for spreading rate provided near this location in Bird (2003), therefore used the value for recent spreading (1.5-2.0 cm/yr half spreading rate) cited in Nicolosi et al. (2006)
Source data: Menini et al., 2023; Rizzo et al., 2022

Location: Smoking Land, Black Point, Hot/Cold, La Calcara, Bottaro
Comment: vents to the E-NE of Panarea Island towards Basiluzzo islet; Basiluzzo area is reported in Gamberi et al. 1997; 1m high Fe-oxide rich chimneys on submerged slopes of volcano; Smithsonian Global Volcanism Program profile 211041, accessed 1 June 2015: "Vigorous hydrothermal activity has continued at fumarolic fields at several locations on the submerged platform, and submarine hydrothermal explosions have occurred in historical time."; 53°C at shallow vents at Panarea Island (Italiano and Nuccio 1991); only a subset of vent sites names are listed: Black Point, Hot Lake, and La Calcara and are provided in Price et al. 2015, Smoking Land, 70-80m depth is provided in Esposito et al. 2018; position in given to Smoking Land vent site;
Source data: Menini et al., 2023; Rizzo et al., 2022

Comment: Vulcano stratovolcano; hydrothermal discharge on shores of volcanic island with precipitation of Fe & Mn oxides, silica, anhydrite, gypsum and pyrite within volcaniclastic sediments; Sedwick and Stueben (1996): "These fluids are interpreted as a mixture of seawater and low-salinity groundwater which has undergone high-temperature (> 100 °C) hydrothermal alteration, followed by mixing with cool seawater in the sub-seafloor and during venting."
Source data: Menini et al., 2023; Rizzo et al., 2022

Comment: Campi Flegrei volcano; wikipedia: "Lying mostly underwater, the area comprises 24 craters and volcanic edifices. Hydrothermal activity can be observed at Lucrino, Agnano and the town of Pozzuoli"; note: Hannington lists with Aeolian Islands, but it is not part of the Aeolian Arc; within the Phlegrean Volcanic District (D'Antonio et al. 2007)
Source data: Menini et al., 2023; Rizzo et al., 2022
MH-shiny DB - ID Ischia-Grotta del Mago

Comment: tectonic setting categorized as "other" based on description in Stueben et al. (1996): "The chemical data suggest that the proposed thermal fluid contains two components, one derived from seawater (< 90%) and the other from low-salinity groundwater (> 10%). The heat source for the circulating fluids is uncertain, but may involve warm underlying igneous rocks or heating via the geothermal gradient."; note: M. Hannington lists with Aeolian Islands, but it is not part of the Aeolian Arc; not part of Palinuro Volcanic Complex
Source data: Menini et al., 2023; Rizzo et al., 2022

Site_Name: Timpa del salto-ampliamento timpa del salto

Comment: The site is located on the southern side of Mount Sara, in "Contrada Cavalieri" and consist in a little mud volcanoes; it can be reached by the local road (SP 31 Cattolica - Cianciana), following for the direction " Bissana". Far few kilometers there is another area located on a hilly relief, immediately sets to north respect Mount Bissana; these manifestations consist in two bubbling salty water polls (named "abisso grande" and "abisso piccolo") wide less than 10 meters, with occasional mud volcanoes.

The area is located less than 2 km south respect the homonym inhabited center, in  Agrigento province. The manifestations have a mean altitude of s 265m a.s.l. and consist in a field of mud volcanoes (with an heigth ranging from few centimetres to half a meter) and some bubbling pools with a maximum diameter of 3.5m, covering an area of 1.4km2

The site is located in the area of the abandoned Athletic Stadium of the "Villaggio Santa Barbara" (hamlet of Caltanissetta)  in "Contrada Terrapelata". The site can easily be reached being situated along one f the principal road (SS 122 Agrigentina). The manifestations consist in a field of mud volcanoes and bubbling pools in a hilly area, with a mean altitude of 500m a.s.l.

This site is located at the NW boundary of the town of PaternÃ², very close to the local football stadium. Gas emissions occur in mud volcanoes or in mud and water pools, with strong gas bubbling into water. The area belongs to the communality of PaternÃ² and is fenced with gates. However, some openings in the fence allow the access to the gas sites.

This site is located some kilometers SW of PaternÃ² in a private property at the border of the valley of the Simeto River. Degassing occurs from many small vents, sometimes from small mud volcanoes but usually from bubbling waters into cm-size water pools. From PaternÃ² take the road from the old railway station towards Sferro. After about 1km take the road that heads to Contrada Fata, and after another kilometer there is a gate to the left, open during the working hours, and a dirty roads that leads you to the degassing area.

This site is characterised by focused degassing that occurs in mud volcanoes located in the open country. The volcanoes have a nice shield shape and occupy an area of about 4500 m2. The area is located a few kilometers SE of the town of Paternò. Access is possible from the road connecting PaternÃ² to Valcorrente. The site is into private property.

Soil diffuse degassing with high CO2 emissions of clearly magmatic origin occurring within a large area characterized by mud volcanoes, with temperature of the muddy waters varying from 16 to 18 ° C and only in some paroxysmal phases (1866, 1879 and 1954) have been recorded temperatures between 46 and 49 ° C.

Salinelle of Simeto River are located west of Paternò near the homonymous river and fluids are released through an undated lava flow that belongs to the Mongibello cycle and is partially covered by recent alluvial deposits. The fluids escaping from these manifestations are composed of a gas phase and hypersaline waters that often pond in pools that range in size from centimeters to meters in diameter.
Area characterized by an intence soil diffuse emission and the presence of three mud volcanoes discharging large amounts of gaes with high CO2 contents.

Soil diffuse emission with high CO2 concentrations and salt deposition in the subsurface, causing poor plant growth and evenabsence of vegetation. Although no mud volcanoes are present in this area, some traces of sporadic emission of salty waters were observed in the past.

Site_Name: San Casciano in Val di Pesa

Comment: Mount Etna is one of the most active volcanoes in the world and is in an almost constant state of activity.  In June 2013, Mt. Etna was added to the list of UNESCO World Heritage Sites. In the specific, the Voragine crater has been formed in 1945 inside the main central crater of the volcano.
Total bulk degassing from the activity of all the four craters present on the top of the Mt Etna volcano.

Mount Etna is one of the most active volcanoes in the world and is in an almost constant state of activity. It is an active stratovolcano on the east coast of Sicily (Italy) which lies above the convergent plate margin between the African Plate and the Eurasian Plate. In June 2013, Mt. Etna was added to the list of UNESCO World Heritage Sites. In the specific, the South East crater has been formed in 1971 inside the main central crater of the volcano.

The North East crater has been formed in 1911 inside the main central crater of the Mt Etna volcano, one of the most active volcanoes in the world which is in an almost constant state of activity with a persistent plume emission, more or less water-rich.

Continuos bulk degassing from the summit active craters located on the terrace of Stromboli volcano. Activity at Stromboli volcano consists of weak to mild explosions of incandescent ejecta at a rate of 3-20 per hour.

Bocca Nuova crater has been formed in 1968 inside the main central crater of Mt Etna volcano, one of the most active volcanoes in the world which is in an almost constant state of activity with a persistent plume emission, more or less water-rich.

This site is located very close to the Ionian Sea coast. It is an artificial water channel with bubbling gas at its bottom through cracks in the concrete floor. The area is into private land. Access is through a gate on a dirty road that starts from the road that goes from Fondachello to the park of Fiumefreddo river.
Borehole in 2004 for thermal purposes. Estimated Altitude (GPS). 58m deep shaft T = 31.9-32.7 C = 38000-56000.  Hotel La Magnolia via Lungomare 18 98021 Terme (ME)
Collection tank with gas bubbling. Estimated Altitude (GPS)
Well slightly spa is no longer used. Estimated Altitude (GPS). Approximately 8m deep well with a few feet of water. T = 20-24 C = 900-1500. Hotel La Magnolia Via Lungomare 18 98021 Terme (ME)

This site is located very close to the Salinella Stadio di PaternÃ². It is a water spring with bubbling gas. The area belongs to the communality of PaternÃ² and recently the site has been restored and now the spring is into an artificial pool. Access is through a gate on a parking place located just north of the old football stadium.
It is the tank a few meters north of ALI03. Gas bubbling. Estimated Altitude (GPS)

The sampling point is just north of the Baths Granata. Near the shore, about 2-3 feet deep, there are several points from which flow of the bubbles and the other where the bottom and 'altered with reddish coloration but where there is no gas emissions. The flow is very low.

The area of ​​exhalation is located in the small concrete buildings that house the tanks for the maturation of the mud. The flow is very low, but all the tanks are located in a depressed area with poor air and strong accumulation in the soil, especially in the tanks.
Gas emission lies in the sea a few meters from the shore.
The point is located in an area of ​​diffuse gaseous emissions of considerable magnitude. The point of emission is greater in correspondence of a black rock block that emerges from the bottom sand.
Significant emissions are easily visible from the surface.

Considerable emission in correspondence with a pit. The site in November 2002 had a significant increase in the gas flow that has dragged with it a considerable amount of debris so as to deepen and widen the hole. Over time, this flow is decreased to return to the values ​​prior to 2002.
The point is home to major gaseous emission, visible from the surface in moments of calm.
The emissions are a low depth. The flow is weak.
Emissions are spread along the beach but are also known small emissions at sea within the port.
Series of small springs with bubbling gas and abundant deposition of iron oxides.
Large diameter (2 m) well. Water rich in bubbling gas and iron oxides.
Small gas emission cosisting in trhee main bubbling pool and diffuse degassing
Gas manifestation and thermal water discharge along the Mignone river at 40th km of the road to Tolfa.
Mineral springs with small gas emission
Close to Caprese Michelangelo, a couple of km from Dicciano, several bubbling pools are easily accessible.
Bubbling water located in the Oliveto Citra area, Other gas emissions are present in the surroundings
Gas emission near the village of Oliveto citra
Methane rich gas emission near the village of Malvizia
Vigorous vent in water pool near the volturno river side
Strong emission of a CO2-rich phase in the Ambra River. Several spots of emission are present one of which has a high flux with the water being displaced of about 30-40 cm
Abandoned travertine quarry. Access is dangerous due to a steep descent.
Inside an abandoned spa. The edifice is rather dangerous, being not stable .
Inside an abandoned spa. The edifice is rather dangerous, being not stable.
On the left-hand side of the road that from Rapolano goes to Serre di Rapolano. The access is relatively difficult due to intense canes that surround the 10 m in diameter gas pool
Along the Malena creek. Bubbles in water. Easy access.
Inside the local thermal spa. It is used to prepare mud for therapeutic purposes
Close to Lajatico. Along a small creek a ca. 1.5 m wide mud pool discharge a CO2-rich gas phase.
Two bubbling pools accessible after a 30 minutes long walk. The area is not indicated by any information. It is a tricky area due to the soft mud that surround the pools
Close to Volterra, an about 1 m wide pool characterized by gentle bubbling
Several small gas pool that discharge along the small creek that flows close to the old CO2 exploitation and mineral bottling factory
Recently restored pool by the local municipality. Thermal bath free of charge
Gas bubbling along the Farma River close to Petriolo Terme. Several manifestations are present in the river and some of them are used a Jacuzzi pool
The CO2-rich spring discharges in the building that in the XIX century was hosting the old Terme di Arezzo.
NE of Amiata Mt. Along the Lavinate creek. Easy access through CAI pathways.
Close to Iano. Two thermal pools discharge relatively gently CO2-rich gas
Small gas pool at the left-hand side of the road after the exit of the Siena Grosseto motorway
200 m2 of diffuse emission with small gas bubbling
CO2-rich discharging thermal spring on the top of a travertine deposit. It is a site of attraction for the tourists who visit Petriolo Terme
Weak bubbling pool close to the old Sb mine
Inside a private garden. A small (1 m x 1 m) pool. Gentle bubbling
Along a small creek several CO2-rich bubbling pools occur
Small thermal spring with associated gentle bubbling. The site is along the Merse River
One of the many thermal spring discharges in which a gas phase gently bubbles. Most of the pools are used for thermal bath
Small gas pool close to the yard of the local CO2 factory
Just close to city of Pienza a 7 m in diameter gas pool occurs. The area is not protected nor indicated being located in wide space.

This manifestation is located in "Le Biancane" area, in the north side of the Monterotondo Marittimo country, it ischaracterized by different kind of thermal manifestations. This manifestation composed by hole 5-6m deep and 7-8m large, rinsed by hot water
Thermal manifestation is near to the Lagoni del Sasso power plant. It is surrounded by thick vegetation and access is free.
Thermal manifestation is composed by hot boiling water pool with steam and gas emission.
Thermal manifestation located on the northern side of the M. "Il Monte", in front of the Sasso Pisano country.
Gas emission associated to the abandoned San Cataldo spa
The area covers approximately 200-300 square meters. It has several pools with gas bubbling along some engravings are found gas emissions from the soil.
Near Ardea S.Stefano spa, bubbling pool on the rigth side of the road

To reach the area of Tolfa you may want to take the 'Roma-Civitavecchia motorway and exit at Civitavecchia NORD. After the toll follow signs for Tolfa. Along this road, Allumiere-Tolfa, are reported from wells U.Ventriglia
From Tolfa road to Bracciano, height Rota where the little white house on the left with a stream on the right.
NE of Amiata Mt. Small series of pools often filled by meteoric water in which CO2 vigourously bubbles

Secca delle Fumose is a small (0.14 km2) ridge-shaped submarine relief located 800 m from the coast in the north-western sector of Pozzuoli Bay.Today there are several thermal vents discharging hot (808C) gas-rich hydrothermal fluids interspersed within the SdF Roman pilae. The isotope composition of the released gas-es (C and He) are similar to those released in the Solfatara-Pisciarelli area, possibly indicating a common fluid origin.

Soil diffuse emissions close to Lake of Venus, a volcanic lake in Pantelleria island.Lake SV is fed by thermal springs that discharge at the stand line. The springs are gaseous, with CO2 as the major constituent (~98 vol.%) and minor amounts of N2, O2, Ar, CH4, H2 and He. The PCO2 of the lake water is in excess of the atmospheric value, so that there is a continuous loss of CO2 fromthe lake surface through bubbling.
Soil diffuse emissions at Vulcanello area, Vulcano island.
Soil diffuse degassing inside the Piano's caldera.
Many small fumarolic emissions and a mud pool are present in the Levante Beach area, with gases reaching a maximum T of 100 °C, located either offshore and in land.
Diffuse emissions at Lentia area, Vulcano island.
Soil diffuse gaseous emissions inside the Campo Sportivo area, Vulcano island.
Soil diffuse degassing at Gelso area, sout-eastern sector of the island.
SW base of La Fossa cone, known for its high CO2 soil concentration and release.

Torre del Filosofo is located in the southern part of Mt Etna volcano, at about 2900 mt of altitude. The legend tales that  this site is the place where Empedocles threw himself into the crater of fire '"Etna Burning."

Soil diffuse degassing along a surface geology consisting of recent alluvial deposits and Plio-Pleistocene clays and sands interbedded with coeval basaltic lavas and pyroclastics of alkaline affinity. Actually, the main gas emission is exploited for commercial use (Mofeta dei Palici plant). This area is also characterized by several water well with warm (20-50 °C) water.

Fluids emitted through marly clays of the foredeep sedimentary deposits are composed of a gas phase and hypersaline waters that often pond in pools that range in size from centimeters to meters in diameter.

The sampling point is located in the side of the local road SP 25 Pollina, at about 8 chilometers from the Pollina Village (PA). This sector of the Madonian Mountains (segment of the Maghrebian-Appenninc Chain) is characterized by recent seismic events of low-medium intensity (i.e earthquake of magnitude 4.7 in June 26, 1993).

The sampling point is located near the local road SP 52,  at about 1 chilometers from the San Mauro Castelverde village (PA). The soil degassing point is placed in the side of the road, in a sismically active sector of the Madonian Mountains (segment of the Maghrebian-Appenninc Chain).

The sampling point is located few meters on the south side of the local road SP32, at about 11 chilometers in SW direction respect castellammare del Golfo (TP). The soil degassing point is placed in free not cultivated field, in an area characterized by active tectonic lineaments and thermal water manifestations (i.e. Terme Segestane and Terme Gorga)

The gaseous manifestation is places in the free beach in locality Fetente (in the east side of the foce of homonymous torrent) just in front of the Aeolian volcanic arc. The beach, composed by sands and pabbles, is reached from Northern Sicilian Statal road (SS 113), through an access to sea, praticable only on foot. In the vicinities is possible to perceive an unmistakable smell of H2S.

The sampling point is located 3 kilometers in SW direction respect to Ispica. In correspondence of a lateral open space with trees and blocks, in the south side of the local road SP46, there is a signpost Grandi Opere di Maria. In corrispondence of the soil degassing point there isn't any type of clear visible form indicating the presents of the manifestation. This area is interested by an important tectonic lineament, the Rosolini-Pozzalo fault system, at which are attributed the historical seismic events of 1727 and 1903.

The sampling point is located at about one kilometer at south from the village Lattarico (CS). The soil degassing point is placed in a sismically active sector of the  Calabrian Coastal Chain, along one of the principal N- S tectonic line in the area, the San Fili - San Marco Argentano fault.

The sampling point is located at about 5 kilometers in S direction respect to Scicli, near the village Cava d'Aliga. The soil degassing point in placed behind a little rock wall, in the side of a local road in Contrada Pagliarelli, in corrispondence of an outcrop of stratified white limestone. This sector of the hyblean plateau is interested by an important active tectonic lineament, the Scicli line, at which are attributed in part the recent seismic events of 1980 and 1990.

Located at about 160 km far from Sicilian coast in the Pelagian Archipelago the Linosa island (about 5.2 km2; 196m a.s.l.) represents the sub-aerial portion of a largest volcanic complex that rise from a depth of 800 m b.s.l., near to south-west sector of the homonymous graben. Representing the most ancient sub-aerial volcanic edifice in the Sicily Channel (1.0 and 0.5 Ma), doesn’t show at present any kind of volcanic activity; only same submarine exhalative manifestation was recognized in correspondence of the top of a submerged relict volcanic structure. In the inland low flux of gas were recognized in some point with an arrangement in according to the regional tectonic setting.The sampling point is placed in the eastern sector of the island, at the base of the eastern flank of the Monte Vulcano and along the perimetral road of the island.

From the Naftia lake go back towards the State Road 447 and turn right at the second intersection. Move around the volcanic hill of Cavoni and after about 2.5 km there is an industrial area. Enter into the first property with a large hovel. The degassing area is right behind the hovel, near a small quarry.

From Zafferana Etnea take the road that goes to Milo. Right after the restaurant "Villa Mirador" turn right at the first bifurcation and then turn left at the first street near an old house. Turn left at the next bifurcation and follow a narrow road bounded by stone walls. Stop at the first house: the degassing area is right around that place.

This site is in the open country, about 2 km SE of Paternò. Access is from a dirty road and the area is into a private property with a barn where horses usually stay. A small wall along the road delimit the properties where degassing occurs. The owners of the land can be often found in the nearby houses.
Degassing area on the beach east of the Well Marino ALI09. Amplitude approximately 8000m2
The issue, mixed with hot steam, is mainly concentrated in a point on the beach around which was built a circle of stones. The issue is still widespread on the beach and even in the sea.
Soil diffuse degassing close to the Favare area, a sector of the island charachterized by jets of water vapor that can reach 100 ° C  by escaping from the rock.
Diffuse soil degassing at Pizzo Sopra La Fossa, summit area of the volcano.
Zafferana Etnea is a pheripheal area of the Etna volcano; it is well known for its high rate gas discharge from soil diffuse degassing.
Medium size diffuse degassing area and water emergence
Diffuse CO2 emission in a pubblic park near Oriolo Romano

This manifestation is located in "Le Biancane" area, in the north side of the Monterotondo Marittimo country. It's characterized by different kind of thermal manifestations.

From Zafferana Etnea take the road that goes to Piano dell'Acqua (a sign indicates the lava flow of 1992). About 200 m before the parking place near the 1992 lava flow take a dirty road to the left. Turn right at the first bifurcation and stop where a chain closes the road. You can continue on foot and after 800 m the road bends to the right and there is the entrance of the gallery.

From Zafferana Etnea take the road that goes to Piano dell'Acqua (a sign indicates the lava flow of 1992). About 200 m before the parking place near the 1992 lava flow take a dirty road to the left. Turn left at the first bifurcation and after some hundreds of meters the dirty roads ends at the entrance of the gallery.

From Santa Venerina take the road called Via Stabilimenti that leads to Giarre. About 600 m after the last houses of the village there is an iron bridge. Right before th ebridge there is a gate on the right that is usually closed. The gate is the entrance of the property where there is the entrance of the gallery, which is closed.
